<emphasis id="B953EA88FF86B14BFC62F871FBE91880" box="[978,1149,1946,1972]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF86B14BFB3AF870FA831880" authorityName="Santschi" authorityYear="1914" box="[1162,1303,1947,1972]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Promyopias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF86B14BFB3AF870FA831880" box="[1162,1303,1947,1972]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Promyopias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF86B14BFEB2F855FE0418EC" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1870" box="[258,400,1982,2008]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Belonopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF86B14BFEB2F855FE0418EC" box="[258,400,1982,2008]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Belonopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF86B14BFE2FF855FDA718E3" authorityName="Forel" authorityYear="1912" box="[415,563,1982,2007]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Emeryopone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF86B14BFE2FF855FDA718E3" box="[415,563,1982,2007]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Emeryopone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF86B14BFDF1F855FD3218E3" authorityName="Roger" authorityYear="1861" box="[577,678,1982,2007]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Myopias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF86B14BFDF1F855FD3218E3" box="[577,678,1982,2007]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Myopias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF86B14BFD6FF855FCC018EC" box="[735,852,1982,2008]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Simopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF86B14BFD6FF855FCC018EC" box="[735,852,1982,2008]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Simopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will be described in forthcoming publications (B.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369AFF87B14AFF53FEDAFD621E5A" blockId="47.[227,1436,305,367]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
Boudinot in prep. and R.S. Probst 
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF87B14AFDDFFED9FD351E7F" box="[623,673,305,331]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">et al</emphasis>
. in prep.). The male of 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFC1FFEDAFBD11E7F" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="1974" box="[943,1093,305,331]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dolioponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF87B14AFC1FFEDAFBD11E7F" box="[943,1093,305,331]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Dolioponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was discovered by the author during the review period of the present work.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369AFF87B14AFF53FE7DFBC61DFD" blockId="47.[227,1437,406,714]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
Unlike the female castes, which have the lateral torular arch fused with the frontal carina (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB64B6BFF87B14AFB48FE7DFA1B1E84" author="Bolton B." box="[1272,1423,406,432]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="1 - 370" refId="ref30019" refString="Bolton B. 2003. Synopsis and classification of Formicidae. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute 71: 1 - 370." type="journal article" year="2003">
<collectingRegion id="49E3F878FF87B14AFB48FE7DFADE1E84" box="[1272,1354,406,432]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bolton" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Bolton</collectingRegion>
2003
</bibRefCitation>
), no single character was found to distinguish male 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFC86FE52FC3F1EE7" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint-Fargeau" authorityYear="1835" box="[822,939,441,467]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ponerinae">Ponerinae</taxonomicName>
from other subfamilies. The 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFAB5FE52FA091EE7" authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1901" box="[1285,1437,441,467]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Platythyreini">Platythyreini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFEA7FE37FEEE1EC2" box="[279,378,476,502]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
share numerous characteristics but are easier to key separately due to the informatively variable development of male mandibles. The 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFCB8FE14FCFF1D2D" box="[776,875,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
themselves are challenging to key as the males of some genera are highly derived, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFCB0FDC8FCE11D09" box="[768,885,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Simopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF87B14AFCB0FDC8FCE11D09" box="[768,885,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Simopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which lacks the mesopleural sulcus and the cinctus of abdominal segment III, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFD03FDADFCDD1D54" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="1974" box="[691,841,582,608]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dolioponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B953EA88FF87B14AFD03FDADFCDD1D54" box="[691,841,582,608]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Dolioponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which also lacks the mesopleural sulcus and has the antennal toruli situated near the anterior head margin. A polythetic definition of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFB55FD82FADC1DB7" box="[1253,1352,617,643]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
is thus required. Fortunately, some of the derived character states of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFC67FD67FBAE1D92" box="[983,1082,652,678]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
also serve to distinguish them from the “generalized” ants, including the 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFD66FD44FCC81DFD" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1809" box="[726,860,687,713]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Formicinae">Formicinae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFC25FD44FBDA1DFD" authorityName="Forel" authorityYear="1878" box="[917,1102,687,713]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Dolichoderinae">Dolichoderinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369AFF87B14AFF53FD1AFBC41B36" blockId="47.[227,1437,753,1026]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<bibRefCitation id="EFB64B6BFF87B14AFF53FD1AFDA21C3F" author="Yoshimura M. &amp; Fisher B. L." box="[227,566,753,779]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="21 - 40" refId="ref33568" refString="Yoshimura M. &amp; Fisher B. L. 2007. A revision of male ants of the Malagasy region (Hymenoptera: Formicidae): key to subfamilies and treatment of the genera of Ponerinae. Zootaxa 1654: 21 - 40." type="journal article" year="2007">Yoshimura &amp; Fisher (2007)</bibRefCitation>
and previously 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB64B6BFF87B14AFCB0FD1AFBE81C3F" author="Yoshimura M. &amp; Onoyama K." box="[768,1148,753,779]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="421 - 443" refId="ref33746" refString="Yoshimura M. &amp; Onoyama K. 2002. Male-based keys to the subfamilies and genera of Japanese ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Entomological Science 5: 421 - 443." type="journal article" year="2002">Yoshimura &amp; Onoyama (2002)</bibRefCitation>
used the scutoscutellar sulcus and conformation of the mesopleural sulcus to diagnose the 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFBA9FCFFFB1A1C1A" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint-Fargeau" authorityYear="1835" box="[1049,1166,788,814]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ponerinae">Ponerinae</taxonomicName>
for the Malagasy and Japanese regions, respectively. These structures are variably developed on the global level, with several genera presenting unsculptured scutoscutellar sulci, and as noted above the mesopleural sulcus is not always present. In general, presence of the abdominal segment III cinctus is more stable than these sulci. Understanding the generic boundaries of male 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFCB3FC4AFCEC1C8F" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint-Fargeau" authorityYear="1835" box="[771,888,929,955]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ponerinae">Ponerinae</taxonomicName>
will be most difficult in the Afrotropics, where the most genera occur and where the least number of genera have males described. A key to the New World genera, including 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D19FF87B14AFDB6FC0CFDEA1B35" authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint-Fargeau" authorityYear="1835" box="[518,638,999,1025]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ponerinae">Ponerinae</taxonomicName>
, is in the works (B. Boudinot, in prep.).
</paragraph>
